      <h2>Building Triads</h2>
      <p>Triads are the basic building blocks of harmony, consisting of three notes stacked in thirds. They form the foundation of chords in Western music and play a vital role in defining tonality and creating musical texture.</p>

      <p>Triads are constructed by stacking thirds on top of a root note. The quality of the triad — major, minor, diminished, or augmented — is determined by the intervals between the root, third, and fifth.</p>

      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Major Triad</dt>
        <dd>Root + major third + perfect fifth. <em>Example in C:</em> <span class="mono">C – E – G</span>.</dd>

        <dt>Minor Triad</dt>
        <dd>Root + minor third + perfect fifth. <em>Example in C:</em> <span class="mono">C – E♭ – G</span>.</dd>

        <dt>Diminished Triad</dt>
        <dd>Root + minor third + diminished fifth. <em>Example in C:</em> <span class="mono">C – E♭ – G♭</span>.</dd>

        <dt>Augmented Triad</dt>
        <dd>Root + major third + augmented fifth. <em>Example in C:</em> <span class="mono">C – E – G♯</span>.</dd>
      </dl>

      <figure>
        <img src="/assets/key-notes.jpg" alt="Diagram showing scale notes for each major key." />
        <figcaption>Scale notes for each major key — the raw material from which triads are built.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure>
        <img src="/assets/key-notes-with-triads.jpg" alt="Diagram showing scale notes alongside the triads built on each scale degree." />
        <figcaption>The same scales, with the diatonic triads built on each scale degree.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <h3>Identifying Triads</h3>
      <p>To identify a triad, recognize the intervals between the notes and the quality those intervals imply. The patterns mirror the construction rules above: a major triad has a major third over the root and a perfect fifth; a minor triad has a minor third and a perfect fifth; a diminished triad stacks a minor third and a diminished fifth; an augmented triad stacks a major third and an augmented fifth.</p>

      <h3>Practical Application</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Chord progressions</strong> — triads are the seed of every progression in a song.</li>
        <li><strong>Harmonic analysis</strong> — recognizing triads reveals the harmonic structure of a piece.</li>
        <li><strong>Performance</strong> — accurate triad reading underpins every chord on every instrument.</li>
        <li><strong>Composition</strong> — triads are the raw material of harmony and texture.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Chords</h2>
      <p>A chord is a group of three or more notes played together to create harmony. Chords are the building blocks of harmony and form the basis of music across genres. They support melodies, create tension and resolution, and convey emotion.</p>

      <h3>Components of a Chord</h3>
      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Root</dt>
        <dd>The note from which the chord takes its name. The foundation upon which the chord is built.</dd>

        <dt>Third</dt>
        <dd>A third interval above the root. Its quality (major or minor) determines whether the chord is major or minor.</dd>

        <dt>Fifth</dt>
        <dd>A fifth interval above the root. Adds stability and support.</dd>

        <dt>Additional notes</dt>
        <dd>Chords can extend beyond the root, third, and fifth — sevenths, ninths, elevenths, and thirteenths add color, tension, and complexity.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h3>Types of Chords</h3>
      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Major Chord</dt>
        <dd>Root + major third + perfect fifth. Bright and happy; conveys positivity and stability.</dd>

        <dt>Minor Chord</dt>
        <dd>Root + minor third + perfect fifth. Darker, sadder; conveys melancholy or introspection.</dd>

        <dt>Diminished Chord</dt>
        <dd>Root + minor third + diminished fifth. Tense and dissonant; creates suspense or instability.</dd>

        <dt>Augmented Chord</dt>
        <dd>Root + major third + augmented fifth. Bright and tense; useful for tension or modulation.</dd>

        <dt>Seventh Chord</dt>
        <dd>A seventh above the root added to a triad. Common types: major seventh, dominant seventh, minor seventh, half-diminished seventh.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h3>Function of Chords</h3>
      <p>Chords serve different harmonic functions within a piece. The <strong>tonic</strong> provides stability; the <strong>dominant</strong> creates tension and pulls back to the tonic; the <strong>subdominant</strong> provides a sense of departure. Chords are arranged into <strong>progressions</strong> that create the harmonic structure of the music and guide its emotional arc.</p>

      <h2>Chord Progressions</h2>
      <p>A chord progression is a series of chords played in succession, forming the harmonic framework of a piece. Each chord is typically a triad or extended chord. Chord progressions are the harmonic counterpart to melody, providing context for the melodic content.</p>

      <h3>Elements of Progressions</h3>
      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Root movement</dt>
        <dd>The motion of root notes determines the direction and character of the progression — ascending, descending, or static.</dd>

        <dt>Harmonic function</dt>
        <dd>Chords serve different functions: tonic (I), dominant (V), subdominant (IV), and others. These functions create tension and resolution.</dd>

        <dt>Cadences</dt>
        <dd>Cadences mark the end of a phrase or section. Common cadences: <strong>authentic</strong> (V–I), <strong>plagal</strong> (IV–I), <strong>deceptive</strong> (V–vi).</dd>
      </dl>

      <h3>Types of Progressions</h3>
      <dl class="deflist">
        <dt>Diatonic</dt>
        <dd>Use chords that belong to the same key or scale; based on the notes of the scale and following traditional patterns.</dd>

        <dt>Modal</dt>
        <dd>Use chords from a specific mode (Ionian, Aeolian, etc.). Often have a distinct tonal color and mood.</dd>

        <dt>Functional</dt>
        <dd>Focus on relationships between chords and their harmonic function within a key. Common examples: I–V–I, circle of fifths.</dd>
      </dl>

      <h2>Common Chord Progressions</h2>
      <p>A handful of progressions form the foundation of countless songs across genres. They provide structure, harmony, and emotional resonance.</p>

      <h3>I–IV–V <span class="muted">(Tonic – Subdominant – Dominant)</span></h3>
      <p>One of the most ubiquitous progressions in Western music. Provides a sense of tension and resolution; common in pop, rock, blues, and folk.</p>
      <p><em>Example in C major:</em> <span class="mono">C (I) – F (IV) – G (V)</span>. Used in "Twist and Shout" by The Beatles and "La Bamba" by Ritchie Valens.</p>

      <h3>I–V–vi–IV <span class="muted">(Tonic – Dominant – Relative Minor – Subdominant)</span></h3>
      <p>Often called the "pop-punk progression" or "sensitive singer-songwriter progression." Favored for its emotive quality and versatility.</p>
      <p><em>Example in C major:</em> <span class="mono">C (I) – G (V) – Am (vi) – F (IV)</span>. Found in "Let It Be" by The Beatles and "With or Without You" by U2.</p>

      <h3>I–vi–IV–V <span class="muted">(Tonic – Relative Minor – Subdominant – Dominant)</span></h3>
      <p>The "50s progression" or "doo-wop progression." A staple of rock and roll, pop, and doo-wop, with a nostalgic, classic sound.</p>
      <p><em>Example in C major:</em> <span class="mono">C (I) – Am (vi) – F (IV) – G (V)</span>. Heard in "Stand By Me" by Ben E. King and "Earth Angel" by The Penguins.</p>

      <h3>ii–V–I <span class="muted">(Supertonic – Dominant – Tonic)</span></h3>
      <p>Fundamental in jazz; also prevalent in classical and contemporary music. Provides a strong sense of resolution.</p>
      <p><em>Example in C major:</em> <span class="mono">Dm (ii) – G (V) – C (I)</span>. Used extensively in jazz standards like "Autumn Leaves" and "Take the A Train."</p>

      <h3>Practical Application</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Songwriting</strong> — common progressions are a foundation for melody, lyrics, and arrangement.</li>
        <li><strong>Arranging</strong> — progressions guide harmonic orchestration across instruments and ensembles.</li>
        <li><strong>Performance</strong> — progressions serve as the basis for accompaniment, improvisation, and covers.</li>
      </ul>

